# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bash-valve
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:bash-valve/adiabatic-expansion] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:bash-valve/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] An **electromagnet** is a type of magnet in which the magnetic field is produced by an electric current.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Electromagnets usually consist of copper wire wound into a coil.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A current through the wire creates a magnetic field which is concentrated along the center of the coil.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The magnetic field disappears when the current is turned off.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The wire turns are often wound around a magnetic core made from a ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic material such as iron; the magnetic core concentrates the magnetic flux and makes a more powerful magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The main advantage of an electromagnet over a permanent magnet is that the magnetic field can be quickly changed by controlling the amount of electric current in the winding.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, unlike a permanent magnet, which needs no power, an electromagnet requires a continuous supply of current to maintain the magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Electromagnets are widely used as components of other electrical devices, such as motors, generators, electromechanical solenoids, relays, loudspeakers, hard disks, MRI machines, scientific instruments, and magnetic separation equipment.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Electromagnets are also employed in industry for picking up and moving heavy iron objects such as scrap iron and steel.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Danish scientist Hans Christian Ørsted discovered in 1820 that electric currents create magnetic fields.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In the same year, the French scientist André-Marie Ampère showed that iron can be magnetized by inserting it into an electrically fed solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] British scientist William Sturgeon invented the electromagnet in 1824.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] His first electromagnet was a horseshoe-shaped piece of iron that was wrapped with about 18 turns of bare copper wire.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] (Insulated wire did not then exist.) The iron was varnished to insulate it from the windings.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When a current was passed through the coil, the iron became magnetized and attracted other pieces of iron; when the current was stopped, it lost magnetization.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Sturgeon displayed its power by showing that although it only weighed seven ounces (roughly 200 grams), it could lift nine pounds (roughly 4 kilos) when the current of a single-cell power supply was applied.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, Sturgeon's magnets were weak because the uninsulated wire he used could only be wrapped in a single spaced-out layer around the core, limiting the number of turns.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Beginning in 1830, US scientist Joseph Henry systematically improved and popularised the electromagnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] By using wire insulated by silk thread and inspired by Schweigger's use of multiple turns of wire to make a galvanometer, he was able to wind multiple layers of wire onto cores, creating powerful magnets with thousands of turns of wire, including one that could support 2,063 lb (936 kg).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The first major use for electromagnets was in telegraph sounders.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The magnetic domain theory of how ferromagnetic cores work was first proposed in 1906 by French physicist Pierre-Ernest Weiss, and the detailed modern quantum mechanical theory of ferromagnetism was worked out in the 1920s by Werner Heisenberg, Lev Landau, Felix Bloch, and others.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A *portative electromagnet* is one designed to just hold material in place; an example is a lifting magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A *tractive electromagnet* applies a force and moves something.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A common tractive electromagnet is a uniformly wound solenoid and plunger.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The solenoid is a coil of wire, and the plunger is made of a material such as soft iron.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Applying a current to the solenoid applies a force to the plunger and may make it move.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The plunger stops moving when the forces upon it are balanced.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For example, the forces are balanced when the plunger is centered in the solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The maximum uniform pull happens when one end of the plunger is at the middle of the solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] where C is a proportionality constant, A is the cross-sectional area of the plunger, N is the number of turns in the solenoid, I is the current through the solenoid wire, and ℓ is the length of the solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For long, slender, solenoids (in units using inches, pounds force, and amperes), the value of C is around 0.009 to 0.010 psi (maximum pull pounds per square inch of plunger cross-sectional area).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For example, a 12-inch-long coil (*ℓ* = 12 in) with a long plunger with a cross section of one inch square (*A* = 1 in2) and 11,200 ampere-turns (*N I* = 11,200 Aturn) had a maximum pull of 8.75 pounds (corresponding to *C* = 0.0094 psi).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The maximum pull is increased when a magnetic stop is inserted into the solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The stop becomes a magnet that will attract the plunger; it adds little to the solenoid pull when the plunger is far away but dramatically increases the pull when the plunger is close.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Here *ℓ*a is the distance between the end of the stop and the end of the plunger.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The additional constant *C*1 for units of inches, pounds, and amperes with slender solenoids is about 2660.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The first term inside the bracket represents the attraction between the stop and the plunger; the second term represents the same force as the solenoid without a stop (**Eq.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Some improvements can be made on this basic design.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The ends of the stop and plunger are often conical.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For example, the plunger may have a pointed end that fits into a matching recess in the stop.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The shape makes the solenoid's pull more uniform as a function of separation.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Another improvement is to add a magnetic return path around the outside of the solenoid (an "iron-clad solenoid").
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The magnetic return path, just as the stop, has little impact until the air gap is small.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] An electric current flowing in a wire creates a magnetic field around the wire, due to Ampere's law *(see drawing of wire with magnetic field)*.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] To concentrate the magnetic field in an electromagnet, the wire is wound into a coil with many turns of wire lying side-by-side.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The magnetic field of all the turns of wire passes through the center of the coil, creating a strong magnetic field there.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A coil forming the shape of a straight tube (a helix) is called a solenoid.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The direction of the magnetic field through a coil of wire can be determined by the right-hand rule.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] If the fingers of the right hand are curled around the coil in the direction of current flow (conventional current, flow of positive charge) through the windings, the thumb points in the direction of the field inside the coil.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The side of the magnet that the field lines emerge from is defined to be the *north pole*.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Much stronger magnetic fields can be produced if a magnetic core, made of a soft ferromagnetic (or ferrimagnetic) material such as iron, is placed inside the coil.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A core can increase the magnetic field to thousands of times the strength of the field of the coil alone, due to the high magnetic permeability $\mu$ of the material.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Not all electromagnets use cores, so this is called a *ferromagnetic-core* or *iron-core* electromagnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This phenomenon occurs because the magnetic core's material (often iron or steel) is composed of small regions called magnetic domains that act like tiny magnets (see ferromagnetism).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Before the current in the electromagnet is turned on, these domains point in random directions, so their tiny magnetic fields cancel each other out, and the core has no large-scale magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When a current passes through the wire wrapped around the core, its magnetic field penetrates the core and turns the domains to align in parallel with the field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] As they align, all their tiny magnetic fields add to the wire's field, which creates a large magnetic field that extends into the space around the magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The core concentrates the field, and the magnetic field passes through the core in lower reluctance than it would when passing through air.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The larger the current passed through the wire coil, the more the domains align, and the stronger the magnetic field is.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Once all the domains are aligned, any additional current only causes a slight increase in the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Eventually, the field strength levels off and becomes nearly constant, regardless of how much current is sent through the windings.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This phenomenon is called saturation, and is the main nonlinear feature of ferromagnetic materials.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For most high-permeability core steels, the maximum possible strength of the magnetic field is around 1.6 to 2 teslas (T).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This is why the very strongest electromagnets, such as superconducting and very high current electromagnets, cannot use cores.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When the current in the coil is turned off, most of the domains in the core material lose alignment and return to a random state, and the electromagnetic field disappears.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, some of the alignment persists because the domains resist turning their direction of magnetization, which leaves the core magnetized as a weak permanent magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This phenomenon is called hysteresis and the remaining magnetic field is called remanent magnetism.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The residual magnetization of the core can be removed by degaussing.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In alternating current electromagnets, such as those used in motors, the core's magnetization is constantly reversed, and the remanence contributes to the motor's losses.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] which says that the integral of the magnetizing field $\mathbf {H}$ around any closed loop is equal to the sum of the current flowing through the loop.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A related equation is the Biot–Savart law, which gives the magnetic field due to each small segment of current.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This equation can be derived from the energy stored in a magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Rearranging terms yields the equation above.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] for the core's saturation limit, $B_{sat}$ .
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In more intuitive units, it is useful to remember that at 1 T the magnetic pressure is approximately 4 standard atmospheres (4.1 kg/cm2).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Given a core geometry, the magnetic field needed for a given force can be calculated from (**Eq.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] 2**); if the result is much more than 1.6 T, a larger core must be used.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, computing the magnetic field and force exerted by ferromagnetic materials in general is difficult for two reasons.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] First, the strength of the field varies from point to point in a complicated way, particularly outside the core and in air gaps, where *fringing fields* and *leakage flux* must be considered.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Second, the magnetic field and force are nonlinear functions of the current, depending on the nonlinear relation between B and $\mathbf {H}$ for the particular core material used.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For precise calculations, computer programs that can produce a model of the magnetic field using the finite element method are employed.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In many practical applications of electromagnets, such as motors, generators, transformers, lifting magnets, and loudspeakers, the iron core is in the form of a loop or magnetic circuit, possibly broken by a few narrow air gaps.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Iron presents much less "resistance" (reluctance) to the magnetic field than air, so a stronger field can be obtained if most of the magnetic field's path is within the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Since the magnetic field lines are closed loops, the core is usually made in the form of a loop.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Since most of the magnetic field is confined within the outlines of the core loop, this allows a simplification of the mathematical analysis.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A common simplifying assumption satisfied by many electromagnets, which will be used in this section, is that the magnetic field strength *B* is constant around the magnetic circuit (within the core and air gaps) and zero outside it.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Most of the magnetic field will be concentrated in the core material (*C*) (see Fig.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Within the core, the magnetic field (*B*) will be approximately uniform across any cross-section; if the core also has roughly constant area throughout its length, the field in the core will be constant.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] At any air gaps (*G*) between core sections, the magnetic field lines are no longer confined by the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Here, they bulge out beyond the core geometry over the length of the gap, reducing the field strength in the gap.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The "bulges" (*BF*) are called fringing fields.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, as long as the length of the gap is smaller than the cross-section dimensions of the core, the field in the gap will be approximately the same as in the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In addition, some of the magnetic field lines (*BL*) will take "short cuts" and not pass through the entire core circuit, and thus will not contribute to the force exerted by the magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This also includes field lines that encircle the wire windings but do not enter the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The magnetic field created by an electromagnet is proportional to both the number of turns of wire N and the current I ; their product, $NI$ , is called magnetomotive force.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This is a nonlinear equation, because the permeability of the core $\mu$ varies with B .
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For an exact solution, $\mu (B)$ must be obtained from the core material hysteresis curve.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] If B is unknown, the equation must be solved by numerical methods.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, if the magnetomotive force is well above saturation (so the core material is in saturation), the magnetic field will be approximately the material's saturation value $B_{sat}$ , and will not vary much with changes in $NI$ .
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For a closed magnetic circuit (no air gap), most core materials saturate at a magnetomotive force of roughly 800 ampere-turns per meter of flux path.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For most core materials, the relative permeability $\mu _{r}\approx 2000{\text{–}}6000\,$ .
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Therefore, in magnetic circuits with an air gap, B depends strongly on the length of the air gap, and the length of the flux path in the core does not matter much.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Given an air gap of 1mm, a magnetomotive force of about 796 ampere-turns is required to produce a magnetic field of 1 T.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For a closed magnetic circuit (no air gap), such as would be found in an electromagnet lifting a piece of iron bridged across its poles, equation (**Eq.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] To maximize the force, a core with a short flux path *L* and a wide cross-sectional area *A* is preferred (this also applies to magnets with an air gap).
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] To achieve this, in applications like lifting magnets and loudspeakers, a flat cylindrical design is often used.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The winding is wrapped around a short wide cylindrical core that forms one pole, and a thick metal housing that wraps around the outside of the windings forms the other part of the magnetic circuit, bringing the magnetic field to the front to form the other pole.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The previous methods are applicable to electromagnets with a magnetic circuit; however, they do not apply when a large part of the magnetic field path is outside the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] (A non-circuit example would be a magnet with a straight cylindrical core.) To determine the force between two electromagnets (or permanent magnets) in these cases, a special analogy called a *magnetic-charge model* can be used.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In this model, it is assumed that the magnets have well-defined "poles" where the field lines emerge from the core, and that the magnetic field is produced by fictitious "magnetic charges" on the surface of the poles.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This model assumes point-like poles (instead of surfaces), and thus it only yields a good approximation when the distance between the magnets is much larger than their diameter; thus, it is useful just for determining a force between them.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] There are several side effects which occur in electromagnets, which must be considered in their design.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] These effects generally become more significant in larger electromagnets.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The only power consumed in a direct current (DC) electromagnet under steady-state conditions is due to the resistance of the windings, and is dissipated as heat.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Some large electromagnets require water cooling systems in the windings to carry off the waste heat.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Since the magnetic field is proportional to the product $NI$ , the number of turns in the windings N and the current I can be chosen to minimize heat losses, as long as their product is constant.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For example, halving I and doubling N halves the power loss, as does doubling the area of the wire.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In either case, increasing the amount of wire reduces the ohmic losses.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] For this reason, electromagnet windings often have a significant thickness.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, the limit to increasing N or lowering the resistance is that the windings take up more space between the magnet's core pieces.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] If the area available for windings is filled up, adding more turns requires a smaller diameter of wire, which has higher resistance, and thus cancels the advantage of using more turns.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] So, in large magnets there is a minimum amount of heat loss that cannot be reduced.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This increases with the square of the magnetic flux, $B^{2}$ .
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] An electromagnet has significant inductance, and resists changes in the current through its windings.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Any sudden changes in the winding current cause large voltage spikes across the windings.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This is because when the current through the magnet is increased, such as when it is turned on, energy from the circuit must be stored in the magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When it is turned off, the energy in the field is returned to the circuit.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] If an ordinary switch is used to control the winding current, this can cause sparks at the terminals of the switch.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This does not occur when the magnet is switched on, because the limited supply voltage causes the current through the magnet and the field energy to increase slowly.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] But when it is switched off, the energy in the magnetic field is suddenly returned to the circuit, causing a large voltage spike and an arc across the switch contacts, which can damage them.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] With small electromagnets, a capacitor is sometimes used across the contacts, which reduces arcing by temporarily storing the current.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] More often, a diode is used to prevent voltage spikes by providing a path for the current to recirculate through the winding until the energy is dissipated as heat.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The diode is connected across the winding, oriented so it is reverse-biased during steady state operation and does not conduct.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When the supply voltage is removed, the voltage spike forward-biases the diode and the reactive current continues to flow through the winding, through the diode, and back into the winding.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] A diode used in this way is called a freewheeling diode or flyback diode.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Large electromagnets are usually powered by variable current electronic power supplies, controlled by a microprocessor, which prevent voltage spikes by accomplishing current changes slowly, in gentle ramps.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] It may take several minutes to energize or deenergize a large magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In powerful electromagnets, the magnetic field exerts a force on each turn of the windings, due to the Lorentz force $q\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B}$ acting on the moving charges within the wire.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The Lorentz force is perpendicular to both the axis of the wire and the magnetic field.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] It can be visualized as a pressure between the magnetic field lines, pushing them apart.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The Lorentz forces increase with *$B^{2}$*.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In large electromagnets the windings must be firmly clamped in place, to prevent motion on power-up and power-down from causing metal fatigue in the windings.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In the Bitter electromagnet design (Fig.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] 2), used in very high-field research magnets, the windings are constructed as flat disks to resist the radial forces, and clamped in an axial direction to resist the axial ones.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] In alternating current (AC) electromagnets, used in transformers, inductors, and AC motors and generators, the magnetic field is constantly changing.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This causes energy losses in their magnetic cores, which is dissipated as heat in the core.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The losses stem from two processes: eddy currents and hysteresis losses.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] When a magnetic field higher than the ferromagnetic limit of 1.6 T is needed, superconducting electromagnets can be used.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Instead of using ferromagnetic materials, these use superconducting windings cooled with liquid helium, which conduct current without electrical resistance.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] These allow enormous currents to flow, which generate intense magnetic fields.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Superconducting magnets are limited by the field strength at which the winding material ceases to be superconducting.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Current designs are limited to 10–20 T, with the current (2017) record of 32 T.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The necessary refrigeration equipment and cryostat make them much more expensive than ordinary electromagnets.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] However, in high-power applications this can be offset by lower operating costs, since after startup no power is required for the windings, since no energy is lost to ohmic heating.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] They are used in particle accelerators and MRI machines.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Both iron-core and superconducting electromagnets have limits to the field they can produce.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Therefore, the most powerful man-made magnetic fields have been generated by *air-core* non-superconducting electromagnets of a design invented by Francis Bitter in 1933, called Bitter electromagnets.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] Instead of wire windings, a Bitter magnet consists of a solenoid made of a stack of conducting disks, arranged so that the current moves in a helical path through them, with a hole through the center where the maximum field is created.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] This design has the mechanical strength to withstand the extreme Lorentz forces of the field, which increase with *$B^{2}$*.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The disks are pierced with holes through which cooling water passes to carry away the heat caused by the high current.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The strongest continuous field achieved solely with a resistive magnet is 41.5 T as of 22 August 2017, produced by a Bitter electromagnet at the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory in Tallahassee, Florida.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The strongest continuous magnetic field overall, 45 T, was achieved in June 2000 with a hybrid device consisting of a Bitter magnet inside a superconducting magnet.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The most powerful man-made magnetic fields have been created by using explosives to compress the magnetic field inside an electromagnet as it is pulsed; these are called explosively pumped flux compression generators.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] The implosion compresses the magnetic field to values of around 1,000 T for a few microseconds.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] While this method may seem very destructive, shaped charges redirect the blast outward to minimize harm to the experiment.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] These devices are known as *destructive pulsed electromagnets*.
[src:bash-valve/electromagnet] They are used in physics and materials science research to study the properties of materials at high magnetic fields.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] A **fire extinguisher** is a handheld active fire protection device filled with extinguishing agents such as dry chemical powder, co2, water, etc. used to extinguish or control small fires, often in emergencies.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It is not intended for use on an out-of-control fire, such as one which has reached the ceiling, endangers the user (i.e., no escape route, smoke, explosion hazard, etc.), or otherwise requires the equipment, personnel, resources or expertise of a fire brigade.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Typically, a fire extinguisher consists of a hand-held cylindrical pressure vessel containing an agent that can be discharged to extinguish a fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishers manufactured with non-cylindrical pressure vessels also exist, but are less common.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] There are two main types of fire extinguishers: stored-pressure and cartridge-operated.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In stored-pressure units, the expellant is stored in the same chamber as the firefighting agent itself.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Depending on the agent used, different propellants are used.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] With dry chemical extinguishers, nitrogen is typically used; water and foam extinguishers typically use air.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Stored pressure fire extinguishers are the most common type.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Cartridge-operated extinguishers contain the expellant gas in a separate cartridge that is punctured before discharge, exposing the propellant to the extinguishing agent.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This type is not as common, used primarily in areas such as industrial facilities, where they receive higher-than-average use.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] They have the advantage of simple and prompt recharge, allowing an operator to discharge the extinguisher, recharge it, and return to the fire in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Unlike stored pressure types, these extinguishers use compressed carbon dioxide instead of nitrogen, although nitrogen cartridges are used on low-temperature (–60 rated) models.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Cartridge-operated extinguishers are available in dry chemical and dry powder types in the U.S. and water, wetting agent, foam, dry chemical (classes ABC and B.C.), and dry powder (class D) types in the rest of the world.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishers are further divided into handheld and cart-mounted (also called wheeled extinguishers).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Handheld extinguishers weigh from 0.5 to 26.76 kilograms (1.1 to 59.0 lb), and are hence easily portable by hand.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Cart-mounted units typically weigh more than 106.6 kilograms (235 lb).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] These wheeled models are most commonly found at construction sites, airport runways, heliports, as well as docks and marinas.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The first fire extinguisher of which there is any record was patented in England in 1723 by Ambrose Godfrey, a celebrated chemist at that time.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It consisted of a cask of fire-extinguishing liquid containing a pewter chamber of gunpowder.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This was connected with a system of fuses which were ignited, exploding the gunpowder and scattering the solution.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This device was probably used to a limited extent, as Bradley's Weekly Messenger for November 7, 1729, refers to its efficiency in stopping a fire in London.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] When operated it expelled liquid onto the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] One of the first fire extinguisher patents was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Martin, an American inventor, was awarded a patent for an improvement in the Fire Extinguishers on March 26, 1872.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Patent Office in Washington, DC under patent number 125,603.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The soda-acid extinguisher was first patented in 1866 by Francois Carlier of France, which mixed a solution of water and sodium bicarbonate with tartaric acid, producing the propellant carbon dioxide (CO2) gas.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] A soda-acid extinguisher was patented in the U.S. in 1880 by Almon M.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] His extinguisher used the reaction between sodium bicarbonate solution and sulfuric acid to expel pressurized water onto a fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] A vial of concentrated sulfuric acid was suspended in the cylinder.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Depending on the type of extinguisher, the vial of acid could be broken in one of two ways.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] One used a plunger to break the acid vial, while the second released a lead stopple that held the vial closed.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Once the acid was mixed with the bicarbonate solution, carbon dioxide gas was expelled and thereby pressurized the water.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The pressurized water was forced from the canister through a nozzle or short length of hose.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The cartridge-operated extinguisher was invented by Read & Campbell of England in 1881, which used water or water-based solutions.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] They later invented a carbon tetrachloride model called the "Petrolex" which was marketed toward automotive use.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The chemical foam extinguisher was invented in 1904 by Aleksandr Loran in Russia, based on his previous invention of fire fighting foam.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Loran first used it to extinguish a pan of burning naphtha.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It worked and looked similar to the soda-acid type, but the inner parts were slightly different.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The main tank contained a solution of sodium bicarbonate in water, whilst the inner container (somewhat larger than the equivalent in a soda-acid unit) contained a solution of aluminium sulphate.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] When the solutions were mixed, usually by inverting the unit, the two liquids reacted to create a frothy foam, and carbon dioxide gas.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The gas expelled the foam in the form of a jet.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Although liquorice-root extracts and similar compounds were used as additives (stabilizing the foam by reinforcing the bubble-walls), there was no "foam compound" in these units.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The foam was a combination of the products of the chemical reactions: sodium and aluminium salt-gels inflated by the carbon dioxide.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Because of this, the foam was discharged directly from the unit, with no need for an aspirating branchpipe (as in newer mechanical foam types).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Special versions were made for rough service, and vehicle mounting, known as apparatus of fire department types.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Key features were a screw-down stopper that kept the liquids from mixing until it was manually opened, carrying straps, a longer hose, and a shut-off nozzle.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire department types were often private label versions of major brands, sold by apparatus manufacturers to match their vehicles.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Examples are Pirsch, Ward LaFrance, Mack, Seagrave, etc.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] These types are some of the most collectable extinguishers as they cross into both the apparatus restoration and fire extinguisher areas of interest.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In 1910, The Pyrene Manufacturing Company of Delaware filed a patent for using carbon tetrachloride (CTC, or CCl4) to extinguish fires.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The liquid vaporized and extinguished the flames by inhibiting the chemical chain reaction of the combustion process (it was an early 20th-century presupposition that the fire suppression ability of carbon tetrachloride relied on oxygen removal).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In 1911, they patented a small, portable extinguisher that used the chemical.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This consisted of a brass or chrome container with an integrated handpump, which was used to expel a jet of liquid towards the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It was usually of 1 imperial quart (1.1 L) or 1 imperial pint (0.57 L) capacity but was also available in up to 2 imperial gallons (9.1 L) size.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] As the container was unpressurized, it could be refilled after use through a filling plug with a fresh supply of CTC.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Another type of carbon tetrachloride extinguisher was the **fire grenade**.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This consisted of a glass sphere filled with CTC, that was intended to be hurled at the base of a fire (early ones used salt-water, but CTC was more effective).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Carbon tetrachloride was suitable for liquid and electrical fires and the extinguishers were fitted to motor vehicles.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Carbon tetrachloride extinguishers were withdrawn in the 1950s because of the chemical's toxicity – exposure to high concentrations damages the nervous system and internal organs.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Additionally, when used on a fire, the heat can convert CTC to phosgene gas, formerly used as a chemical weapon.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The carbon dioxide extinguisher was invented (at least in the US) by the Walter Kidde Company in 1924 in response to Bell Telephone's request for an electrically non-conductive chemical for extinguishing the previously difficult-to-extinguish fires in telephone switchboards.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It consisted of a tall metal cylinder containing 7.5 pounds (3.4 kg) of CO2 with a wheel valve and a woven brass, cotton-covered hose, with a composite funnel-like horn as a nozzle.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] CO2 is still popular today as it is an ozone-friendly clean agent and is used heavily in film and television production to extinguish burning stuntmen.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Carbon dioxide extinguishes fire mainly by displacing oxygen.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It was once thought that it worked by cooling, although this effect on most fires is negligible.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Also in 1887, carbonic acid gas was described as a fire extinguisher for engine chemical fires at sea and ashore.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In 1928, DuGas (later bought by ANSUL) came out with a cartridge-operated dry chemical extinguisher, which used sodium bicarbonate specially treated with chemicals to render it free-flowing and moisture-resistant.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It consisted of a copper cylinder with an internal CO2 cartridge.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The operator turned a wheel valve on top to puncture the cartridge and squeezed a lever on the valve at the end of the hose to discharge the chemical.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This was the first agent available for large-scale three-dimensional liquid and pressurized gas fires, but remained largely a specialty type until the 1950s, when small dry chemical units were marketed for home use.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] ABC dry chemical came over from Europe in the 1950s, with Super-K being invented in the early 1960s and Purple-K being developed by the United States Navy in the late 1960s.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Manually applied dry agents such as graphite for class D (metal) fires had existed since World War II, but it was not until 1949 that Ansul introduced a pressurized extinguisher using an external CO2 cartridge to discharge the agent.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Met-L-X (sodium chloride) was the first extinguisher developed in the US, with graphite, copper, and several other types being developed later.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In the 1940s, Germany invented the liquid chlorobromomethane (CBM) for use in aircraft.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It was more effective and slightly less toxic than carbon tetrachloride and was used until 1969.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Methyl bromide was discovered as an extinguishing agent in the 1920s and was used extensively in Europe.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] It is a low-pressure gas that works by inhibiting the chain reaction of the fire and is the most toxic of the vaporizing liquids, used until the 1960s.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The vapor and combustion by-products of all vaporizing liquids were highly toxic and could cause death in confined spaces.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In the 1970s, Halon 1211 came over to the United States from Europe where it had been used since the late 1940s or early 1950s.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Halon 1301 had been developed by DuPont and the United States Army in 1954.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Both 1211 and 1301 work by inhibiting the chain reaction of the fire, and in the case of Halon 1211, cooling class A fuels as well.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Halon is still in use today but is falling out of favor for many uses due to its environmental impact.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Europe and Australia have severely restricted its use, since the Montreal Protocol of 1987.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Less severe restrictions have been implemented in the United States, the Middle East, and Asia.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Internationally there are several accepted classification methods for hand-held fire extinguishers.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Each classification is useful in fighting fires with a particular group of fuel.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Specifications of fire extinguishers are set out in the standard AS/NZS 1841, the most recent version having been released in 2007.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] All fire extinguishers must be painted *signal red*.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Except for water based extinguishers, each extinguisher has a coloured band near the top, covering at least 10% of the extinguisher's body length, specifying its contents.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Due to the ozone-depleting nature of halon, in Australia yellow (Halon) fire extinguishers are illegal to own or use on a fire, unless an essential use exemption has been granted.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] According to British standard BS EN 3, fire extinguishers in the United Kingdom, same as throughout Europe, are red RAL 3000, with a band or circle of a second color covering between 5–10% of the surface area of the extinguisher, above the operating instructions, indicating its contents.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Before 1997, the entire body of the fire extinguisher was color coded according to the type of extinguishing agent.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Class E has been discontinued, previously covering fires involving electrical hazards.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] This is no longer used on the basis that, when the power supply is turned off, an electrical fire can fall into any of the remaining five categories.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] EN3 does however allow extinguishers to bear a special electrical pictogram signifying that it can be used on live electrical fires (given the symbol E in the table), if it passes special testing (a 35 kV dielectric test per EN 3-7:2004).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] A powder or CO2 extinguisher will feature this as standard.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] A water-based extinguisher may feature it if it passes the 35 kV test, however all water-based extinguishers are only recommended for inadvertent use on electrical fires.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In the UK, the use of Halon gas is now prohibited except under certain situations such as on aircraft and in the military and police.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishing performance per fire class is displayed using numbers and letters such as 13A, 55B.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] There is no official standard in the United States for the color of fire extinguishers, though they are usually red, except for class D extinguishers which are usually yellow, water and Class K wet chemical extinguishers which are usually silver, and water mist extinguishers which are usually white.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Extinguishers are marked with pictograms depicting the types of fires that the extinguisher is approved to fight.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In the past extinguishers were marked with colored geometric symbols, and some extinguishers still use both symbols.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The types of fires and additional standards are described in *NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers, 2013 edition*.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishing capacity is rated in accordance with *ANSI/UL 711: Rating and Fire Testing of Fire Extinguishers*.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The ratings are described using numbers preceding the class letter, such as 1-A:10-B:C.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The number preceding the A multiplied by 1.25 gives the equivalent extinguishing capability in gallons of water.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The number preceding the B indicates the size of fire in square feet that an ordinary user should be able to extinguish.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] There is no additional rating for class C, as it only indicates that the extinguishing agent will not conduct electricity, and an extinguisher will never have a rating of just C.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishers are usually fitted in buildings at an easily accessible location, such as against a wall in a high-traffic area.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] They are also often fitted to motor vehicles, watercraft, and aircraft – this is required by law in many jurisdictions, for identified classes of vehicles.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Under NFPA 10 all commercial vehicles must carry at least one fire extinguisher, with size/UL rating depending on type of vehicle and cargo (i.e., fuel tankers usually must have a 20 lb (9.1 kg), while most others can carry a 5 lb (2.3 kg)).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Varying classes of competition vehicles require fire extinguishing systems, the simplest requirements being a 1A:10BC hand-held portable extinguisher mounted to the interior of the vehicle.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The height limit for installation, as determined by the NFPA, is 60 in (1.5 m) for fire extinguishers weighing less than 40 lb (18 kg).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] However, compliance with the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) also needs to be followed within the United States.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The ADA height limit of the fire extinguisher, as measured at the handle, is 48 in (1.2 m).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguisher installations are also limited to protruding no more than 4 inches into the adjacent path of travel.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The ADA rule states that any object adjacent to a path of travel may not project more than 4 in (10 cm) if the object's bottom leading edge is higher than 27 in (0.69 m).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The 4-inch protrusion rule was designed to protect people with low-vision and those who are blind.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] The height limit rule of 48 inches is primarily related to access by people with wheelchairs but it is also related to other disabilities as well.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Prior to 2012, the height limit was 54 in (1.4 m) for side-reach by wheelchair-accessible installations.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Installations made prior to 2012 at the 54-inch height are not required to be changed.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] In New Zealand, the mandatory installation of fire extinguishers in vehicles is limited to self-propelled plant in agriculture and arboriculture, passenger service vehicles with more than 12 seats and vehicles that carry flammable goods.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] NZ Transport Agency recommends that all company vehicles carry a fire extinguisher, including passenger cars.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p01] Fire extinguishers mounted inside aircraft engines are called *extinguishing bottles* or *fire bottles*.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Different types of extinguishing agents have different modes of action, and certain ones are only appropriate for specific fire classes.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] This is a powder-based agent that extinguishes by separating the three parts of the fire triangle.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] It prevents the chemical reactions involving heat, fuel, and oxygen, thus extinguishing the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] During combustion, the fuel breaks down into free radicals, which are highly reactive fragments of molecules that react with oxygen.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The substances in dry chemical extinguishers can stop this process.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Applied to fuel fires as either an aspirated (mixed and expanded with air in a branch pipe) or nonaspirated form to create a frothy blanket or seal over the fuel, preventing oxygen reaching it.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Unlike powder, foam can be used to progressively extinguish fires without flashback.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Water cools burning carbonaceous material and is very effective against fires in furniture, fabrics, etc.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Water-based extinguishers cannot be used safely on energized electrical fires or flammable liquid fires.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Additives can be used to alter the properties of water extinguishers, though additives not specified by the manufacturer will void the extinguisher's listing.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Generally, class A and K (F in Europe) only, although older models also achieved class B and C fire-fighting capability in the past, current models are rated A:K (Amerex, Ansul, Buckeye and Strike First) or K only (Badger/Kidde).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Clean agents extinguish fire by displacing oxygen (CO2 or inert gases), removing heat from the combustion zone (Halotron I, FE-36, Novec 1230) or inhibiting the chemical chain reaction (Halons, Halotron BrX).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] They are referred to as clean agents because they do not leave any residue after discharge, which is ideal for protecting sensitive electronics, aircraft, armored vehicles and archival storage, museums, and valuable documents.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] There are several class D fire extinguisher agents available; some will handle multiple types of metals, others will not.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Most class D extinguishers will have a special low-velocity nozzle or discharge wand to gently apply the agent in large volumes to avoid disrupting any finely divided burning materials.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Agents are also available in bulk and can be applied with a scoop or shovel.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Several modern "ball" or grenade-style extinguishers are available on the market.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The modern version of the ball is a hard foam shell, wrapped in fuses that lead to a small black powder charge within.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The ball bursts shortly after contact with flame, dispersing a cloud of ABC dry chemical powder which extinguishes the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The coverage area is about 5 m2 (54 sq ft).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] One benefit of this type is that it may be used for passive suppression.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The ball can be placed in a fire-prone area and will deploy automatically if a fire develops, being triggered by heat.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] They may also be manually operated by rolling or tossing into a fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Most modern extinguishers of this type are designed to make a loud noise upon deployment.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] From about 1880 glass "fire grenades" filled with a weak solution of common salt and ammonium chloride in water were popular.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The addition of the salts was to prevent freezing, with ammonium chloride thought to be more effective in extinguishing flame.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] They were deployed by hurling them at the base of the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Containing only about one imperial pint (0.57 L), they were of limited use.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Some later brands, such as Red Comet, were designed for passive operation and included a special holder with a spring-loaded trigger that would break the glass ball when a fusible link melted, or were sealed with wax to melt in contact with flame and release the contents.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] As was typical of this era, some glass extinguishers contained the toxic (but effective) carbon tetrachloride.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] These glass fire grenade bottles are sought after by collectors.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Fire extinguisher pressure vessels have traditionally used cylindrical geometry.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] In 2019, Czech company Amplla received EN 3-7 certification for a flat, ring-shaped pressure vessel design.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The unit measures approximately 80-90 mm in depth and contains 4-6 kg of ABC dry powder at 15 bar operating pressure.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Condensed aerosol fire suppression is a particle-based form of fire extinction similar to gaseous fire suppression or dry chemical fire extinction.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] As with gaseous fire suppressants, condensed aerosol suppressants use clean agents to suppress the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The agent can be delivered by means of mechanical operation, electric operation, or combined electro-mechanical operation.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Whereas dry chemical systems must be directly aimed at the flame, condensed aerosols are flooding agents and therefore effective regardless of the location and height of the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Wet chemical systems, such as the kind generally found in foam extinguishers, must, similarly to dry chemical systems, be sprayed directionally, onto the fire.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Additionally, wet chemicals (such as potassium carbonate) are dissolved in water, whereas the agents used in condensed aerosols are microscopic solids.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] In 2015, researchers from George Mason University announced that high volume sound with low bass frequencies in the 30 to 60 hertz range drives oxygen away from the combustion surface, extinguishing the fire, a principle was previously tested by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] One proposed application is to extinguish fires in outer space, with none of the clean-up required for mass-based systems.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Another proposed solution for fire extinguishers in space is a vacuum cleaner that extracts the combustible materials.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Most countries in the world require regular fire extinguisher maintenance by a competent person to operate safely and effectively, as part of fire safety legislation.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Lack of maintenance can lead to an extinguisher not discharging when required, or rupturing when pressurized.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Deaths have occurred, even in recent times, from corroded extinguishers exploding.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] In the United States, state and local fire codes, as well as those established by federal agencies such as the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, are generally consistent with standards established by the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] They commonly require, for fire extinguishers in all buildings other than single-family dwellings, inspections every 30 days to ensure the unit is pressurized and unobstructed (done by an employee of the facility) and an annual inspection and service by a qualified technician.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Some jurisdictions require more frequent service.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The servicer places a tag on the extinguisher to indicate the type of service performed (annual inspection, recharge, new fire extinguisher).
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Hydrostatic pressure testing for all types of extinguishers is also required, generally every five years for water and CO2 models up to every 12 years for dry chemical models.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Recently the NFPA and ICC voted to allow for the elimination of the 30-day inspection requirement so long as the fire extinguisher is monitored electronically.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] According to NFPA, the system must provide record keeping in the form of an electronic event log at the control panel.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] The system must also constantly monitor an extinguisher's physical presence, internal pressure and whether an obstruction exists that could prevent ready access.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] In the event that any of the above conditions are found, the system must send an alert to officials so they can immediately rectify the situation.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] Electronic monitoring can be wired or wireless.
[src:bash-valve/fire-extinguisher-p02] This also alerts maintenance to check an extinguisher for usage so that it may be replaced if it has been used.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Lienhard points out the Mozi – based on a Chinese text from the Warring States period (475–221 BCE) – as having given the first description of inertia.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Before the European Renaissance, the prevailing theory of motion in western philosophy was that of Aristotle (384–322 BCE).
[src:bash-valve/inertia] On the surface of the Earth, the inertia property of physical objects is often masked by gravity and the effects of friction and air resistance, both of which tend to decrease the speed of moving objects (commonly to the point of rest).
[src:bash-valve/inertia] This misled the philosopher Aristotle to believe that objects would move only as long as force was applied to them.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Aristotle said that all moving objects (on Earth) eventually come to rest unless an external power (force) continued to move them.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Aristotle explained the continued motion of projectiles, after being separated from their projector, as an (itself unexplained) action of the surrounding medium continuing to move the projectile.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Despite its general acceptance, Aristotle's concept of motion was disputed on several occasions by notable philosophers over nearly two millennia.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] For example, Lucretius (following, presumably, Epicurus) stated that the "default state" of the matter was motion, not stasis (stagnation).
[src:bash-valve/inertia] In the 6th century, John Philoponus criticized the inconsistency between Aristotle's discussion of projectiles, where the medium keeps projectiles going, and his discussion of the void, where the medium would hinder a body's motion.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Philoponus proposed that motion was not maintained by the action of a surrounding medium, but by some property imparted to the object when it was set in motion.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Although this was not the modern concept of inertia, for there was still the need for a power to keep a body in motion, it proved a fundamental step in that direction.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] This view was strongly opposed by Averroes and by many scholastic philosophers who supported Aristotle.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] However, this view did not go unchallenged in the Islamic world, where Philoponus had several supporters who further developed his ideas.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] In the 11th century, Persian polymath Ibn Sina (Avicenna) claimed that a projectile in a vacuum would not stop unless acted upon.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] In the 14th century, Jean Buridan rejected the notion that a motion-generating property, which he named *impetus*, dissipated spontaneously.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Buridan's position was that a moving object would be arrested by the resistance of the air and the weight of the body which would oppose its impetus.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Buridan also maintained that impetus increased with speed; thus, his initial idea of impetus was similar in many ways to the modern concept of momentum.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Buridan also believed that impetus could be not only linear but also circular in nature, causing objects (such as celestial bodies) to move in a circle.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Buridan's theory was followed up by his pupil Albert of Saxony (1316–1390) and the Oxford Calculators, who performed various experiments which further undermined the Aristotelian model.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Their work in turn was elaborated by Nicole Oresme who pioneered the practice of illustrating the laws of motion with graphs.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Benedetti cites the motion of a rock in a sling as an example of the inherent linear motion of objects, forced into circular motion.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] The term "inertia" was first introduced by Johannes Kepler in his *Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae* (published in three parts from 1617 to 1621).
[src:bash-valve/inertia] However, the meaning of Kepler's term, which he derived from the Latin word for "idleness" or "laziness", was not quite the same as its modern interpretation.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Kepler defined inertia only in terms of resistance to movement, once again based on the axiomatic assumption that rest was a natural state which did not need explanation.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] It was not until the later work of Galileo and Newton unified *rest* and *motion* in one principle that the term "inertia" could be applied to those concepts as it is today.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] The principle of inertia, as formulated by Aristotle for "motions in a void", includes that a mundane object tends to resist a change in motion.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] The Aristotelian division of motion into mundane and celestial became increasingly problematic in the face of the conclusions of Nicolaus Copernicus in the 16th century, who argued that the Earth is never at rest, but is actually in constant motion around the Sun.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] This observation ultimately came to be the basis for Albert Einstein to develop the theory of special relativity.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Despite having defined the concept in his laws of motion, Newton did not actually use the term "inertia.” In fact, he originally viewed the respective phenomena as being caused by "innate forces" inherent in matter which resist any acceleration.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Given this perspective, and borrowing from Kepler, Newton conceived of "inertia" as "the innate force possessed by an object which resists changes in motion", thus defining "inertia" to mean the *cause* of the phenomenon, rather than the phenomenon itself.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] However, Newton's original ideas of "innate resistive force" were ultimately problematic for a variety of reasons, and thus most physicists no longer think in these terms.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] As no alternate mechanism has been readily accepted, and it is now generally accepted that there may not be one that we can know, the term "inertia" has come to mean simply the phenomenon itself, rather than any inherent mechanism.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Thus, ultimately, "inertia" in modern classical physics has come to be a name for the same phenomenon as described by Newton's first law of motion, and the two concepts are now considered to be equivalent.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Albert Einstein's theory of special relativity, as proposed in his 1905 paper entitled "On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies", was built on the understanding of inertial reference frames developed by Galileo, Huygens and Newton.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] While this revolutionary theory did significantly change the meaning of many Newtonian concepts such as mass, energy, and distance, Einstein's concept of inertia remained at first unchanged from Newton's original meaning.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] However, this resulted in a limitation inherent in special relativity: the principle of relativity could only apply to inertial reference frames.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] To address this limitation, Einstein developed his general theory of relativity ("The Foundation of the General Theory of Relativity", 1916), which provided a theory including *noninertial* (accelerated) reference frames.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] In general relativity, the concept of inertial motion got a broader meaning.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Taking into account general relativity, inertial motion is any movement of a body that is not affected by forces of electrical, magnetic, or other origin, but that is only under the influence of gravitational masses.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Physically speaking, this happens to be exactly what a properly functioning three-axis accelerometer is indicating when it does not detect any proper acceleration.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] The term inertia comes from the Latin word *iners*, meaning idle or sluggish.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] A quantity related to inertia is *rotational inertia* (→ moment of inertia), the property that a rotating rigid body maintains its state of uniform rotational motion.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Its angular momentum remains unchanged unless an external torque is applied; this is called conservation of angular momentum.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] Rotational inertia is often considered in relation to a rigid body.
[src:bash-valve/inertia] For example, a gyroscope uses the property that it resists any change in the axis of rotation.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Based in Davidson, North Carolina, Ingersoll Rand operates in two segments: Industrial Technologies and Services and Precision and Science Technologies.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Simon Ingersoll founded Ingersoll Rock Drill Company in 1871 in New York, and in 1888, it combined with Sergeant Drill to form Ingersoll Sergeant Drill Company.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Also in 1871, brothers Addison Rand and Jasper Rand, Jr. established Rand Drill Company with its main manufacturing plant in Tarrytown, New York.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Rand drills cleared New York's treacherous Hell Gate channel and were used in the construction of water aqueducts for New York City and Washington, D.C., as well as tunnels in Haverstraw and West Point, New York, and in Weehawken, New Jersey.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 1905, Ingersoll-Sergeant Drill Company merged with the Rand Drill Company to form Ingersoll Rand.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In the 1920s, Ingersoll Rand supplied diesel engines for locomotives built by both General Electric and ALCO.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 2000, Ingersoll-Dresser Pumps, formed in 1992 as a joint venture between Ingersoll Rand and Dresser Industries and later a wholly-owned subsidiary, was sold to Flowserve for $775 million.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] The deal made Flowserve the world's second largest pump company.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 2004, it sold Dresser-Rand, another joint-venture with Dresser Industries which merged the two companies' compressor businesses, to First Reserve Corporation for $1.2 billion.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Robert Gardner founded the Gardner Governor Company in 1859 in Quincy, Illinois and introduced an early effective speed controls for steam engines.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] This innovation, known as the flyball governor, helped pave the way for the later production of other industrial products such as air compressors.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] By the turn of the century, the company had sold more than 150,000 governors across the United States and Canada.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] The Gardner Governor Company merged with the Denver Rock Drill Company in 1927 to form Gardner-Denver.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Gardner Denver grew during the early decades of the 1900s and transformed through acquisitions.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 1943, Gardner Denver was listed on the New York Stock Exchange for the first time.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In the late 1950s, merger negotiations with Dresser Industries yielded no agreement, and the same outcome occurred with Cooper-Bessemer.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 1979, Gardner Denver was acquired by C-B's successor, Cooper Industries Inc.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 1994, Cooper spun off the Gardner Denver Industrial Machinery Division as an independent company.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Gardner Denver Inc traded on the New York Stock Exchange until it was acquired by private equity firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Gardner Denver returned to public ownership in 2017 through an initial public offering (IPO), with KKR & Co retaining a 35% stake.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Deferred stock units were granted to permanent employees, some 6,000 people, as part of KKR & Co.'s "employee engagement strategy", which came to be worth approximately $100 million following the IPO.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 2020, Gardner Denver merged with Ingersoll-Rand plc's industrial segment through a Reverse Morris Trust transaction, and took on the name of Ingersoll Rand.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] The new company was worth $15 billion, and Gardner Denver and Ingersoll Rand shareholders held 49.9% and 50.1% of the shares respectively. $150 million in stock were granted to some 16,000 employees.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Ingersoll-Rand plc's HVAC segment, which brought in $12.8 billion in revenue in 2018, became Trane Technologies.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In 2021, KKR & Co. divested from Ingersoll Rand, having made a profit of $4 billion since it acquired Gardner Denver in 2013.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] As of July 2021, Ingersoll Rand operates with two business segments.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In April 2021, a controlling interest in its High Pressure Solutions segment was sold to American Industrial Partners for $278 million.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In June 2021, Club Car, previously Ingersoll Rand's Specialty Vehicles Technologies segment, was sold to Platinum Equity Advisors for $1.68 billion.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In October 2022, Ingersoll Rand announced it would acquire Everest Group, an India-based manufacturer of blowers and vacuum systems and Airmax Groupe, a French manufacturer of compressed air systems.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] In February 2024, Ingersoll Rand acquired Friulair, a company out of Friuli, Italy which specializes in chillers and dryers.
[src:bash-valve/ingersoll-rand] Ingersoll Rand paid a lump sum of $146 million.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] An **isothermal process** is a type of thermodynamic process in which the temperature *T* of a system remains constant: Δ*T* = 0.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] This typically occurs when a system is in contact with an outside thermal reservoir, and a change in the system occurs slowly enough to allow the system to be continuously adjusted to the temperature of the reservoir through heat exchange (see quasi-equilibrium).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In contrast, an *adiabatic process* is where a system exchanges no heat with its surroundings (*Q* = 0).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The noun *isotherm* is derived from the Ancient Greek words ἴσος (*ísos*), meaning "equal", and θέρμη (*thérmē*), meaning "heat".
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Isothermal processes can occur in any kind of system that has some means of regulating the temperature, including highly structured machines, and even living cells.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Some parts of the cycles of some heat engines are carried out isothermally (for example, in the Carnot cycle).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In the thermodynamic analysis of chemical reactions, it is usual to first analyze what happens under isothermal conditions and then consider the effect of temperature.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Phase changes, such as melting or evaporation, are also isothermal processes when, as is usually the case, they occur at constant pressure.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Isothermal processes are often used as a starting point in analyzing more complex, non-isothermal processes.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Isothermal processes are of special interest for ideal gases.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] This is a consequence of Joule's second law which states that the internal energy of a fixed amount of an ideal gas depends only on its temperature.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Thus, in an isothermal process the internal energy of an ideal gas is constant.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] This is a result of the fact that in an ideal gas there are no intermolecular forces.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Note that this is true only for ideal gases; the internal energy depends on pressure as well as on temperature for liquids, solids, and real gases.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In the isothermal compression of a gas there is work done on the system to decrease the volume and increase the pressure.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Doing work on the gas increases the internal energy and will tend to increase the temperature.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] To maintain the constant temperature energy must leave the system as heat and enter the environment.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] If the gas is ideal, the amount of energy entering the environment is equal to the work done on the gas, because internal energy does not change.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For isothermal expansion, the energy supplied to the system does work on the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In either case, with the aid of a suitable linkage the change in gas volume can perform useful mechanical work.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For details of the calculations, see calculation of work.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For an adiabatic process, in which no heat flows into or out of the gas because its container is well insulated, *Q* = 0.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] If there is also no work done, i.e. a free expansion, there is no change in internal energy.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For an ideal gas, this means that the process is also isothermal.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Thus, specifying that a process is isothermal is not sufficient to specify a unique process.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For the special case of a gas to which Boyle's law applies, the product *pV* (*p* for gas pressure and *V* for gas volume) is a constant if the gas is kept at isothermal conditions.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The value of the constant is *nRT*, where *n* is the number of moles of the present gas and *R* is the ideal gas constant.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In other words, the ideal gas law *pV* = *nRT* applies.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The family of curves generated by this equation is shown in the graph in Figure 1.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Each curve is called an isotherm, meaning a curve at a same temperature *T*.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Such graphs are termed indicator diagrams and were first used by James Watt and others to monitor the efficiency of engines.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The temperature corresponding to each curve in the figure increases from the lower left to the upper right.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] where *p* for gas pressure and *V* for gas volume.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For an isothermal (constant temperature *T*), reversible process, this integral equals the area under the relevant PV (pressure-volume) isotherm, and is indicated in purple in Figure 2 for an ideal gas.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In IUPAC convention, work is defined as work on a system by its surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] If, for example, the system is compressed, then the work is done on the system by the surrounding so the work is positive and the internal energy of the system increases.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Conversely, if the system expands (i.e., system surrounding expansion, so free expansions not the case), then the work is negative as the system does work on the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] It is also worth noting that for ideal gases, if the temperature is held constant, the internal energy of the system *U* also is constant, and so Δ*U* = 0.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Since the first law of thermodynamics states that Δ*U* = *Q* + *W* in IUPAC convention, it follows that *Q* = −*W* for the isothermal compression or expansion of ideal gases.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The reversible expansion of an ideal gas can be used as an example of work produced by an isothermal process.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Of particular interest is the extent to which heat is converted to usable work, and the relationship between the confining force and the extent of expansion.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] During isothermal expansion of an ideal gas, both *p* and *V* change along an isotherm with a constant *pV* product (i.e., constant *T*).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Consider a working gas in a cylindrical chamber 1 m high and 1 m2 area (so 1m3 volume) at 400 K in static equilibrium.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The surroundings consist of air at 300 K and 1 atm pressure (designated as *psurr*).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The working gas is confined by a piston connected to a mechanical device that exerts a force sufficient to create a working gas pressure of 2 atm (state A).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For any change in state A that causes a force decrease, the gas will expand and perform work on the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Isothermal expansion continues as long as the applied force decreases and appropriate heat is added to keep *pV* = 2 [atm·m3] (= 2 atm × 1 m3).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The expansion is said to be internally reversible if the piston motion is sufficiently slow such that at each instant during the expansion the gas temperature and pressure is uniform and conform to the ideal gas law.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Figure 3 shows the *p*–*V* relationship for *pV* = 2 [atm·m3] for isothermal expansion from 2 atm (state A) to 1 atm (state B).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The work done (designated $W_{A\to B}$ ) has two components.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] First, *expansion* work against the surrounding atmosphere pressure (designated as *W**p*Δ*V*), and second, usable *mechanical* work (designated as *W*mech).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The output *W*mech here could be movement of the piston used to turn a crank-arm, which would then turn a pulley capable of lifting water out of flooded salt mines.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The system attains state B (*pV* = 2 [atm·m3] with *p* = 1 atm and *V* = 2 m3) when the applied force reaches zero.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] By difference, *W*mech = –39.1 kJ, which is 27.9% of the heat supplied to the process (- 39.1 kJ / - 140.5 kJ).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] This is the maximum amount of usable mechanical work obtainable from the process at the stated conditions.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The percentage of *W*mech is a function of *pV* and *p*surr, and approaches 100% as *p*surr approaches zero.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] To pursue the nature of isothermal expansion further, note the red line on Figure 3.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The fixed value of *pV* causes an exponential increase in piston rise vs. pressure decrease.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For example, a pressure decrease from 2 to 1.9 atm causes a piston rise of 0.0526 m.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In comparison, a pressure decrease from 1.1 to 1 atm causes a piston rise of 0.1818 m.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] where *Q*rev is the heat transferred (internally reversible) to the system and *T* is absolute temperature.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] This formula is valid only for a hypothetical reversible process; that is, a process in which equilibrium is maintained at all times.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] A simple example is an equilibrium phase transition (such as melting or evaporation) taking place at constant temperature and pressure.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] For a phase transition at constant pressure, the heat transferred to the system is equal to the enthalpy of transformation, Δ*H*tr, thus *Q* = Δ*H*tr.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] At any given pressure, there will be a transition temperature, *T*tr, for which the two phases are in equilibrium (for example, the normal boiling point for vaporization of a liquid at one atmosphere pressure).
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Another example is the reversible isothermal expansion (or compression) of an ideal gas from an initial volume *V*A and pressure *P*A to a final volume *V*B and pressure *P*B.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Once obtained, these formulas can be applied to an irreversible process, such as the free expansion of an ideal gas.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Such an expansion is also isothermal and may have the same initial and final states as in the reversible expansion.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Since entropy is a state function (that depends on an equilibrium state, not depending on a path that the system takes to reach that state), the change in entropy of the system is the same as in the reversible process and is given by the formulas above.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] Note that the result *Q* = 0 for the free expansion can not be used in the formula for the entropy change since the process is not reversible.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] The difference between the reversible and irreversible is found in the entropy of the surroundings.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In both cases, the surroundings are at a constant temperature, *T*, so that Δ*S*sur = −⁠*Q*/*T*⁠; the minus sign is used since the heat transferred to the surroundings is equal in magnitude and opposite in sign to the heat *Q* transferred to the system.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In the reversible case, the change in entropy of the surroundings is equal and opposite to the change in the system, so the change in entropy of the universe is zero.
[src:bash-valve/isothermal-expansion] In the irreversible, *Q* = 0, so the entropy of the surroundings does not change and the change in entropy of the universe is equal to ΔS for the system.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A **lawn mower** (also known as a **grass cutter** or simply mower, also often spelled **lawnmower**) is a device utilizing one or more revolving blades (or a reel) to cut a grass surface to an even height.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The height of the cut grass may be fixed by the mower's design but generally is adjustable by the operator, typically by a single master lever or by a mechanism on each of the machine's wheels.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The blades may be powered by manual force, with wheels mechanically connected to the cutting blades so that the blades spin when the mower is pushed forward, or the machine may have a battery-powered or plug-in electric motor.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The most common self-contained power source for lawn mowers is a small 4-stroke (typically one-cylinder) internal combustion engine.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Smaller mowers often lack any form of self-propulsion, requiring human power to move over a surface; "walk-behind" mowers are self-propelled, requiring a human only to walk behind and guide them.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Larger lawn mowers are usually either self-propelled "walk-behind" types or, more often, are "ride-on" mowers that the operator can sit on and control.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A robotic lawn mower ("lawn-mowing bot", "mowbot", etc.) is designed to operate either entirely on its own or less commonly by an operator on a remote control.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Two main styles of blades are used in lawn mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] There are several types of mowers, each suited to a particular scale and purpose.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The smallest types, non-powered push mowers, are suitable for small residential lawns and gardens.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Electrical or piston engine-powered push-mowers are used for larger residential lawns (although there is some overlap).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Riding mowers, which sometimes resemble small tractors, are larger than push mowers and are suitable for large lawns.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] However, commercial riding lawn mowers (such as zero-turn mowers) can be "stand-on" types and often bear little resemblance to residential lawn tractors, being designed to mow large areas at high speed in the shortest time possible.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The largest multi-gang (multi-blade) mowers are mounted on tractors and are designed for large expanses of grass such as golf courses and municipal parks, although they are ill-suited for complex terrain.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The lawn mower was invented in 1830 by Edwin Beard Budding of Stroud, Gloucestershire, England.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Budding's mower was designed primarily to cut the grass on sports grounds and extensive gardens, as a superior alternative to the scythe, and was granted a British patent on August 31, 1830.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Budding's first machine was 19 inches (480 mm) wide with a frame made of wrought iron.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Cast-iron gear wheels transmitted power from the rear roller to the cutting cylinder, allowing the rear roller to drive the knives on the cutting cylinder; the ratio was 16:1.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Another roller placed between the cutting cylinder and the main or land roller could be raised or lowered to alter the height of cut.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The grass clippings were hurled forward into a tray-like box.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] It was soon realized, however, that an extra handle was needed in front to help pull the machine along.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Overall, these machines were remarkably similar to modern mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Two of the earliest Budding machines sold went to Regent's Park Zoological Gardens in London and the Oxford colleges.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In an agreement between John Ferrabee and Edwin Budding dated May 18, 1830, Ferrabee paid the costs of enlarging the small blades, obtained letters of patent and acquired rights to manufacture, sell and license other manufacturers in the production of lawn mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Without patent, Budding and Ferrabee were shrewd enough to allow other companies to build copies of their mower under licence, the most successful of these being Ransomes of Ipswich, which began making mowers as early as 1832.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] His machine was the catalyst for the preparation of modern-style sporting ovals, playing fields (pitches), grass courts, etc.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] This led to the codification of modern rules for many sports, including for football, lawn bowls, lawn tennis and others.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] It took ten more years and further innovations to create a machine that could be drawn by animals, and sixty years before a steam-powered lawn mower was built.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In the 1850s, Thomas Green & Son of Leeds introduced a mower called the Silens Messor (meaning silent cutter), which used a chain drive to transmit power from the rear roller to the cutting cylinder.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These machines were lighter and quieter than the gear-driven machines that preceded them, although they were slightly more expensive.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The rise in popularity of lawn sports helped prompt the spread of the invention.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Lawn mowers became a more efficient alternative to the scythe and domesticated grazing animals.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Manufacture of lawn mowers took off in the 1860s.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] By 1862, Ferrabee's company was making eight models in various roller sizes.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] He manufactured over 5000 machines until production ceased in 1863.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The first grass boxes were flat trays but took their present shape in the 1860s.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] James Sumner of Lancashire patented the first steam-powered lawn mower in 1893.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] His machine burned petrol and/or paraffin (kerosene) as fuel.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These were heavy machines that took several hours to warm up to operating pressure.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] After numerous advances, these machines were sold by the Stott Fertilizer and Insecticide Company of Manchester and Sumner.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The company they both controlled was called the Leyland Steam Motor Company.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Around 1900, one of the best known English machines was the Ransomes' Automaton, available in chain- or gear-driven models.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Numerous manufacturers entered the field with petrol (gasoline) engine-powered mowers after the start of the 20th century.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In 1902, The first was produced by Ransomes.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] JP Engineering of Leicester, founded after World War I, produced a range of very popular chain-driven mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] About this time, an operator could ride behind animals that pulled the large machines.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The first United States patent for a reel lawn mower was granted to Amariah Hills on January 12, 1868.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In 1870, Elwood McGuire of Richmond, Indiana designed a human-pushed lawn mower, which was very lightweight and a commercial success.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] John Burr patented an improved rotary-blade lawn mower in 1899, with the wheel placement altered for better performance.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Amariah Hills went on to found the Archimedean Lawn Mower Co. in 1871.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In the United States, gasoline-powered lawn mowers were first manufactured in 1914 by Ideal Power Mower Co. of Lansing, Michigan, based on a patent by Ransom E.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Ideal Power Mower also introduced the world's first self-propelled, riding lawn tractor in 1922, known as the "Triplex".
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The roller-drive lawn mower has changed very little since around 1930.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] *Gang mowers*, those with multiple sets of blades to cut a wider swath, were built in the United States in 1919 by the Worthington Mower Company.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In the 1920s one of the most successful companies to emerge during this period was Atco, at that time a brand name of Charles H Pugh Ltd.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The Atco 'Standard' motor mower, launched in 1921 was an immediate success.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Just 900 of the 22-inch-cut machines were made in 1921, each costing £75.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Within five years, annual production had accelerated to tens of thousands.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Prices were reduced and a range of sizes were available, making the Standard the first truly mass-produced engine-powered mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Rotary mowers were not developed until engines were small enough and powerful enough to run the blades at sufficient speed.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Many people experimented with rotary blade mowers in the late 1920s and early 1930s, and Power Specialties Ltd. introduced a gasoline-powered rotary mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Kut Kwick replaced the saw blade of the "Pulp Saw" with a double-edged blade and a cutter deck, converting the "Pulp Saw" into the first ever out-front rotary mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] One company that produced rotary mowers commercially was the Australian Victa company, starting in 1952.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Its mowers were lighter and easier to use than similar ones that had come before.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The first Victa mowers were made at Mortlake, an inner suburb of Sydney, by local resident Mervyn Victor Richardson.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] He made his first model out of scrap in his garage.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The first Victa mowers were then manufactured, going on sale on 20 September 1952.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The new company, Victa Mowers Pty Ltd, was incorporated on 13 February 1953.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Two Victa mowers, from 1958 and 1968 respectively, are held in the collection of the National Museum of Australia.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The Victa mower is regarded as something of an Australian icon, appearing en masse, in simulated form, at the opening of the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The hover mower, first introduced by Flymo in 1964, is a form of rotary mower using an air cushion on the hovercraft principle.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A cylinder mower or reel mower carries a fixed, horizontal cutting blade at the desired height of cut.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Over this is a fast-spinning reel of blades which force the grass past the cutting bar.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Each blade in the blade cylinder forms a helix around the reel axis, and the set of spinning blades describes a cylinder.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Of all the mowers, a properly adjusted cylinder mower makes the cleanest cut of the grass, and this allows the grass to heal more quickly.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The cut of a well-adjusted cylinder mower is straight and definite, as if cut with a pair of scissors.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] This clean cut promotes healthier, thicker and more resilient lawn growth that is more resistant to disease, weeds and parasites.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Lawn cut with a cylinder mower is less likely to result in yellow, white or brown discolouration as a result of leaf shredding.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] While the cutting action is often likened to that of scissors, it is neither necessary nor desirable for the blades of the spinning cylinder to contact the horizontal cutting bar.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] When the reel touches the cutting bar the work required by the mower increases dramatically.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] When the gap between the blades is less than the thickness of the grass blades, a clean cut can still be made without additional friction.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] When the gap is greater than the thickness of the grass blades, grass will slip through the gap uncut.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Reel mowers also have more difficulty mowing over uneven terrain.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] There are many variants of the cylinder mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Push mowers have no engine and are usually used on smaller lawn areas where access is a problem, where noise pollution is undesirable and where air pollution is unwanted.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] As the mower is pushed along, the wheels drive gears which rapidly spin the reel.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Typical cutting widths are 10 to 16 inches (250 to 410 mm).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Advances in materials and engineering have resulted in these mowers being very light and easy to operate and manoeuvre compared with their predecessors while still giving all the cutting advantages of professional cylinder mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Their distinct environmental benefits, both in noise and air pollution, are also strong selling points, something not lost on many international zoos, animal sanctuaries and exclusive hotel groups.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The basic push mower mechanism is also used in gangs towed behind a tractor.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The individual mowers are arranged in a "v" behind the tractor with each mower's track slightly overlapping that of the mower in front of it.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Gang mowers are used over large areas of turf such as sports fields or parks.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A gasoline engine or electric motor can be added to a cylinder mower to power the cylinder, the wheels, the roller, or any combination of these.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A typical arrangement on electric powered machines for residential lawns is for the motor to power the cylinder while the operator pushes the mower along.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The electric models can be corded or cordless.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] On petrol machines the engine drives both the cylinder and the rear roller.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Some variants have only three blades in a reel spinning at great speed, and these models are able to cut grass which has grown too long for ordinary push mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] One type of reel mower, now largely obsolete, was a powered version of the traditional side-wheel push mower, which was used on residential lawns.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] An internal combustion engine sat atop the reel housing and drove the wheels, usually through a belt.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The wheels in turn drove the reel, as in the push mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Greens mowers are used for the precision cutting of golf greens and have a cylinder made up of at least eight, but normally ten, blades.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The machine has a roller before and after the cutting cylinder which smooths the freshly cut lawn and minimizes wheel marks.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Due to the weight, the engine also propels the mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Much smaller and lighter variants of the roller mower are sometimes used for small patches of ornamental lawns around flower beds, and these have no engine.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Typically, the cutting reels are ahead of the vehicle's main wheels, so that the grass can be cut before the wheels push the grass over onto the ground.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The reels are often hydraulically powered.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A rotary mower rotates about a vertical axis with the blade spinning at high speed relying on impact to cut the grass.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] This tends to result in a rougher cut and bruises and shreds the grass leaf resulting in discolouration of the leaf ends as the shredded portion dies.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] This is particularly prevalent if the blades become clogged or blunt.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Most rotary mowers need to be set a little higher than cylinder equivalents to avoid scalping and gouging of slightly uneven lawns, although some modern rotaries are fitted with a rear roller to provide a more formal striped cut.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These machines will also tend to cut lower (13 mm or 1⁄2 in) than a standard four-wheeled rotary.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Extensive grass trimming was not common before the widespread application of the vertical shaft single cylinder gasoline/petrol engine.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In the United States this development paralleled the market penetration of companies such as the Briggs & Stratton company of Wisconsin.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Most rotary push mowers are powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Such engines are usually four-stroke engines, used for their greater torque and cleaner combustion (although a number of older models used two-stroke engines), running on gasoline (petrol) or other liquid fuels.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Internal combustion engines used with lawn mowers normally have only one cylinder.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Power generally ranges from four to seven horsepower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The engines usually have a carburetor and require a manual pull crank to start them, although an electric starter is offered on some models, particularly large riding and commercial mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Some mowers have a throttle control on the handlebar with which the operator can adjust the engine speed.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Other mowers have a fixed, pre-set engine speed.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] All are equipped with a governor (often centrifugal/mechanical or air vane style) to open the throttle as needed to maintain the pre-selected speed when the force needed to cut the thicker or taller grass is encountered.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Gasoline mowers have the advantages over electric mowers of greater power and distance range.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] They do create a significant amount of pollution due to the combustion in the engine, and their engines require periodic maintenance such as cleaning or replacement of the spark plug and air filter, and changing the engine oil.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] California passed Assembly Bill 1356 an air pollution control law on October 9, 2021.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The California bill barred sales of spark ignited (gasoline fueled) internal combustion engines less than 25HP used for farm or construction machines as of January 1, 2024.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The California bill does not ban turf care machines larger than 25HP or those powered by compression ignition (diesel) engines.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Electric mowers are further subdivided into corded and cordless electric models.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Both are relatively quiet, typically producing less than 75 decibels, while a gasoline lawn mower can be 95 decibels or more.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Corded electric mowers are limited in range by their trailing power cord, which may limit their use with lawns extending outward more than 100–150 feet (30–45 m) from the nearest available power outlet.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] There is the additional hazard with these machines of accidentally mowing over the power cable, which stops the mower and may put users at risk of receiving a dangerous electric shock.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Installing a residual-current device (GFCI) on the outlet may reduce the shock risk.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Cordless electric mowers are powered by a variable number (typically 1–4) of 12-to-80-volt rechargeable batteries.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Typically, more batteries mean more run time and/or power (and more weight).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Batteries can be in the interior of the lawnmower or on the outside.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] If on the outside, the depleted batteries can be quickly swapped with recharged batteries.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Cordless mowers have the maneuverability of a gasoline-powered mower and the environmental friendliness of a corded electric mower, but they are more expensive and come in fewer models (particularly the self-propelling type) than either.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The eventual disposal of worn-out batteries is problematic (though some manufacturers offer to recycle them), and the motors in some cordless mowers tend to be less powerful than gasoline motors of the same total weight (including batteries).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Cutter and propulsion is powered with a mixture of electricity and fuel.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Sometimes the combustion engine is only used to recharge batteries or power electric motors and does not directly power the cutter or propulsion.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Lawn mowers powered by propane were also manufactured by Lehr.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In hand-powered lawn mowers, the reel is attached to the mower's wheels by gears, so that when the mower is pushed forward, the reel spins several times faster than the plastic or rubber-tired wheels turn.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Depending on the placement of the reel, these mowers often cannot cut grass very close to lawn obstacles.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A robotic lawn mower is an autonomous robot used to cut lawn grass.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A typical robotic lawn mower (in particular earlier generation models) requires the user to set up a border wire around the lawn that defines the area to be mowed.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The robot uses this wire to locate the boundary of the area to be trimmed and in some cases to locate a recharging dock.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Robotic mowers are capable of maintaining up to 100,000 m2 (25 acres) of grass.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Robotic lawn mowers are increasingly sophisticated, are self-docking and some contain rain sensors if necessary, nearly eliminating human interaction.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Robotic lawn mowers represented the second largest category of domestic robots used by the end of 2005.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The drives for these mowers are in several categories.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The most common transmission for tractors is a manual transmission.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The second most common transmission type is a form of continuously variable transmission, called hydrostatic transmission.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These transmissions take several forms, from pumps driving separate motors, which may incorporate a gear reduction, to fully integrated units containing a pump, motor and gear reduction.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Hydrostatic transmissions are more expensive than mechanical transmissions, but they are easier to use and can transmit greater torque to the wheels compared to a typical mechanical transmission.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The least common drive type, and the most expensive, is electric.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] There have been a number of attempts to replace hydrostatic transmissions with lower cost alternatives, but these attempts, which include variable belt types, e.g.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] MTD's "Auto Drive", and toroidal, have various performance or perception problems that have caused their market life to be short or their market penetration to be limited.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Riding lawn mowers can often mount other devices, such as rototillers/rotavators, snow plows, snow blowers, yard vacuums, occasionally even front buckets or fork-lift tines (these are more properly known as "lawn tractors" in this case, being designed for a number of tasks).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The ability to tow other devices is because they have multiple gears, often up to 5 or 6 and variable top speeds.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Compact utility tractors equipped with a belly mower can look similar to riding lawn mowers, but they are typically larger, equipped with diesel engines, and feature a three-point hitch and rollover protection structure; these features are generally absent on riding lawn mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The deck of a rotary mower is typically made of steel.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Lighter steel is used on less expensive models, and heavier steel on more expensive models for durability.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Other deck materials include aluminium, which does not rust and is a staple of higher priced mowers, and hard composite plastic, which does not rust and is lighter and less expensive than aluminium.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Electric mowers typically have a plastic deck.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Riding mowers typically have an opening in the side or rear of the housing where the cut grass is expelled, as do most rotary lawn mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Some have a grass catcher attachment at the opening to bag the grass clippings.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Mower manufacturers market their mowers as side discharge, 2-in-1, meaning bagging and mulching or side discharging and mulching, and 3-in-1, meaning bagging, mulching, and side discharge.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Most 2-in-1 bagging and mulching mowers require a separate attachment to discharge grass onto the lawn.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Some side discharge mower manufacturers also sell separate "mulching plates" that will cover the opening on the side discharge mower and, in combination with the proper blades, will convert the mower to a mulching mower.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These conversions are impractical when compared with 2- or 3-in-1 mowers which can be converted in the field in seconds.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A rear bag mower features an opening on the back of the mower through which the grass is expelled into the bag.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Hi-vac mowers have a tunnel that extends from the side discharge to the bag.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Hi-vac is also the type of grass collection used on some riding lawn mowers and lawn tractors and is suitable for use in dry conditions but less suitable for long wet lush grass as they often clog up.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Mulching and bagging mowers are not well suited to long grass or thick weeds.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In some ride-on mowers, the cut grass is dropped onto the ground and then collected by a set of rotating bristles, allowing even long, wet grass to be collected.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Rotary mowers with internal combustion engines come in three price ranges.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Low priced mowers use older technology, smaller motors, and lighter steel decks.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These mowers are targeted at the residential market and typically price is the most important selling point.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Some lawn mowers are designed to support grasscycling, a practice in which finely cut grass clippings are left on the lawn surface to decompose and return nutrients to the soil rather than being collected and removed.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Professional grass-cutting equipment, used by large establishments such as universities, sports stadiums and local authorities, usually take the form of much larger, dedicated, ride-on platforms or attachments that can be mounted on, or behind, a standard tractor unit (a "gang-mower").
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Either type may use rotating-blade or cylindrical-blade type cutters, although high-quality mowed surfaces demand the latter.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Wide-area mowers (WAMs) are commercial grade mowers which have decks extended to either side, many to 12 feet (3.7 m).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] These extensions can be lowered for large area mowing or raised to decrease the mower's width and allow for easy transport on city roads or trailers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Commercial lawn-mowing companies have also enthusiastically adopted types such as the zero-turn mower (in both ride-on and stand-on versions), which allow high speed over the grass surface, and rapid turnaround at the end of rows, as well as excellent maneuverability around obstacles.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Mowers mounted on a tractor's three-point hitch may be known as *finish mowers* used for maintaining lawn, *flail mowers* used for maintaining rough grass on rough surfaces, or *brush mowers* used for cutting brush and small trees.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Rotary mowers can throw out debris with extreme velocity and energy.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Additionally, the blades of a self-powered push mower (gasoline or electric) can injure a careless or inattentive user; consequently, many come equipped with a dead man's switch to immediately disable the blade rotation when the user is no longer holding the handle.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In the United States, over 12,000 people per year are hospitalized as a result of lawn mower accidents.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] In 2016, 86,000 adults and 4,500 children were admitted to the emergency room for lawnmower injuries.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The vast majority of these injuries can be prevented by wearing protective footwear when mowing.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Persons using a mower should wear heavy footwear, eye protection, and hearing protection in the case of engine-powered mowers.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A 2001 study showed that some mowers produce the same amount of pollution (emissions other than carbon dioxide) in one hour as driving a 1992 model vehicle for 650 miles (1,050 km).
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Another estimate puts the amount of pollution from a lawn mower at four times the amount from a car, per hour, although this report is no longer available.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Beginning in 2011, the United States Environmental Protection Agency set standards for lawn equipment emissions and expects a reduction of at least 35 percent.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Gas powered lawn mowers produce GHG emissions.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] A minimum-maintained lawn management practice with clipping recycling, and minimum irrigation and mowing, is recommended to mitigate global warming effects from urban turfgrass system.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Battery-powered lawn mowers offer cleaner alternatives to consumers by producing zero emissions, being more efficient, and eliminating risks of spilled gasoline.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] However, this can be offset due to the process of mining and refining the lithium contained within some models of the batteries.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Gasoline-powered lawnmowers are not regulated to have emission-capturing technology.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Mowers can create significant noise pollution, and could cause hearing loss if used without hearing protection for prolonged periods of time.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Lawn mowers also present an occupational hearing hazard to the nearly one million people who work in lawn service and ground-keeping.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] The risk of hearing loss and noise pollution can be reduced by using battery-operated mowers or appropriate hearing protection such as earplugs or earmuffs.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] It is possible for a lawn mower to damage the underlying soil, the roots of the grass, and the mower itself if the blades cut through the grass and collide with the underlying ground.
[src:bash-valve/lawnmower] Therefore, it is important to adjust mower height properly and choose the right tires for a lawn mower to prevent any marking or digging.
